Learning Outcomes

Important
  1. Initiate an R Project:
    • Create and organise an R project, including subfolders for datasets and output files.
    • Create a reproducible report via an RMarkdown file.
  2. File I/O:
    • Use read.csv to read data from CSV files into R.
    • Use write.csv to write data from R to CSV files.
  3. Numerical Summaries:
    • Use summary() to get basic statistics.
  4. Graphical Summaries:
    • Use boxplot, plot or ggplot to visualize data.
  5. Data Manipulation:
    • Use subset to filter and subset data based on given conditions.

Initiate an R Project

Follow the instructional video to ensure that you are currently working within an R project named STAT5003. Make sure Sonar.csv has been downloaded from Canvas and saved in a folder named datasets. Additionally, have an RMarkdown file open named wk2_workshop.rmd and be ready to continue the workshop questions in this file.

  1. To create a new data frame called mine from the sonar dataset that contains observations where the Class is M (metal cylinder), you can modify the cereal example
Code 
Kelloggs <- subset(cereal, mfr == "K")

Code 
library(tidyverse)
mine <- sonar |> filter(Class == "M")

Numerical summary

  • Summary
  • Basic statistics
  1. Use the summary function to extract the median, 1st quartile and 3rd quartile data from the V1 column in sonar data. Given its mean and median, what do you think of the shape of V1 data distribution?
summary(sonar$V1)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
0.00150 0.01335 0.02280 0.02916 0.03555 0.13710

Since the mean is greater than its median, we expect the data distribution for V1 to be right skewed.

  1. Use max(), min(), sd(), mean() to find the max, min, standard deviation and mean of V1.
max(sonar$V1)
[1] 0.1371
min(sonar$V1)
[1] 0.0015
sd(sonar$V1)
[1] 0.02299091
mean(sonar$V1)
[1] 0.02916394
  1. The aggregate function can be used to calculate summary statistics for a given level of a categorical variable. Below is an example code that demonstrates how to find the mean sodium for each mfr in the cereal data. Modify the code to find the median V1 of each Class.
Code 
aggregate(sodium ~ mfr, data = cereal, FUN = mean)
#| echo: true
#| code-fold: true
#| message: false


aggregate(V1 ~ Class, data = sonar, FUN = median)
  Class     V1
1     M 0.0269
2     R 0.0201
# Alternatively, in tidyverse select the 'V1' and 'Class' columns from the 'sonar' data frame, group by 'Class', and calculate the median content for each group.
sonar |>
    select(V1, Class) |>
    group_by(Class) |>
    summarise(med = median(V1))
# A tibble: 2 Ã 2
  Class    med
  <chr>  <dbl>
1 M     0.0269
2 R     0.0201

Graphical summary

  • Boxplot
  • Scatter plot
  • Write Data to File
  1. Make a boxplot of the V1 against Class using boxplot().
Code 
# Create a boxplot of V1 content by Class using base R.
# labels for both axes and give a meaningful title
boxplot(V1 ~ Class, data = sonar,
        xlab = "Class", ylab = "V1 content", main = "V1 Content by Class")
Code 
# Using ggplot2.

sonar |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = Class, y = V1)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  theme_classic() + 
  labs(x =  "Class", y = "V1 content") +
  ggtitle("V1 Content by Class")
  1. Plot V2 against V1 using plot().
Code 
# Create a scatter plot of calories versus V1 using base R.
# The plot has the title "Calories versus V1 Scatter Plot".
plot(V2 ~ V1, data = sonar, main = "V2 versus V1 Scatter Plot")
Code 
# Create a scatter plot of calories versus V1 using ggplot2.
# Add a linear regression line without the confidence interval.
# The plot has the title "Calories versus V1 Scatter Plot".
sonar |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = V1, y = V2)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(x =  "V1", y = "V2") +
  ggtitle("V2 versus V1 Scatter Plot")
  1. Use write.csv to write a data frame containing only the M (medal cylinder) observations to a file called mine.
write.csv(mine, here("datasets", "mine.csv"))
